Variables description

Variable Description
PUF_ID It is the unique identification number for each Medicare user interviewed
DEM_SEX Gender of the Medicare user
DEM_RACE Race of the Medicare user
DEM_INCOME Income group of the medicare user
INS_PRIVRX Does the private plan cover Rx drugs?
INS_PRIVLTC Does the private plan cover nursing home?
INS_PRIVVIS Does the private plan cover vision?
INS_PRIVDS Does the private plan cover dental?
INS_D_MADV Are you enrolled in Medicare Advantage?
INS_D_PRIVNUM Do you have one or more private plans?
INS_D_PRIVNUMC How many private plans do you have?
ACC_MCAVAIL What is your level of satisfaction with the medical care offered on nights and weekends?
ACC_MCEASE What is your level of satisfaction with how easy is to get a doctor from home?
ACC_MCCOSTS What is your level of satisfaction with the out-of-pocket costs for medical services?
ACC_MCSAMLOC What is your level of satisfaction with the location of your Medicare?
MA_MADVDENT Does your Medicare Advantage plan cover dental?
MA_MADVEYE Does your Medicare Advantage plan cover eyes exams?
MA_MADVNH Does your Medicare Advantage plan covers nursing home?

Let’s see the first records

head(df)


Note that the values of each column are represented in numbers. Each number represents a category. We will see the description of each number later in the data exploration. For our analysis, we are not going to change the values, considering that in the way they are, they are ideal for our analysis process.


Checking missing values

names(which(colSums(is.na(df))>0))
## [1] "MA_MADVDENT" "MA_MADVEYE"  "MA_MADVNH"

The above columns contain missing values. However, we decided not to manipulate the missing values in any way, considering that those three columns depend on the variable INS_D_MADV. In other words, the missing value here means that that question doesn’t apply to the Medicare User because they don’t have Medicare Advantage Plan. We must consider this situation when analyzing those variables.

Distribution of Level of Satisfaction


Click here to see code 


# Select only the satisfaction variables
items <- select(df, starts_with(c("ACC")))

# Rename the items so that the question statement becomes the name
names(items) <- c(
  ACC_MCAVAIL="Medicare Service at night or weekends",
  ACC_MCEASE="Easy to get to Doctro from Home",
  ACC_MCCOSTS="Out-of-pocket costs for medicare services",
  ACC_MCSAMLOC="Medicare at same location")

# A custom function to recode numerical responses into ordered factors
likert_recode <- function(x) {
  y <- ifelse(is.na(x), NA,
              ifelse(x == 1, "Very Satisfied",
                     ifelse(x == 2, "Satisfied",
                            ifelse(x == 3, "Dissatisfied", "Very Dissatisfied"))))
  
  y <- factor(y, levels = c("Very Satisfied", "Satisfied", "Dissatisfied", "Very Dissatisfied"))
  
  return(y)
}

# Transform the items into factors and save the data set as a likert object
items_likert <- items %>%
  mutate_all(likert_recode) %>%
  likert()

# Create a stacked bar chart
p8 <- plot(items_likert, 
     group.order=names(items),
     plot.percents = TRUE,
     plot.percent.low = FALSE,
     plot.percent.high = FALSE,
     centered = FALSE,
     wrap=30) + 
  labs(title = "Medicare Satisfaction")


As shown in the plot above, it could be observed that 25% of the population are very satisfied and 36% are satisfied with the Medicare service at night and weekend while 4% are dissatisfied and 35% are very dissatisfied with the Medicare service at night and weekend.

Also, it could be depicted that 44% of the population are very satisfied and 50% are satisfied with being able to get to the doctor from home while 4% are dissatisfied and and 3% are very dissatisfied with being able to get to the doctor from home.

Similarly, it could be deduced that 32% of the population are very satisfied and 50% are satisfied with Out-of-pocket costs for medicare services while 12% are dissatisfied and 7% are very dissatisfied with Out-of-pocket costs for medicare services.

In addition, we can infer that 30% of the population are very satisfied and 48% are satisfied with Medicare at same location while 7% are dissatisfied and 14% are very dissatisfied with Medicare at same location.


Level of satisfaction by Income Group and Race


Click here to see code 
satisfaction <- df %>% select(PUF_ID, DEM_SEX, DEM_RACE, DEM_INCOME, ACC_MCAVAIL, ACC_MCEASE, ACC_MCCOSTS, ACC_MCSAMLOC)

# Transform the data from wide format to long format
data_long <- mutate(satisfaction,
                    # Create categorical inccome Group and Race variables
                    income = ifelse(DEM_INCOME == 1, "<$25,000", ">=$25,000"),
                    race = factor(
                      ifelse(is.na(DEM_RACE), NA, 
                                         ifelse(DEM_RACE == 1, "Non-Hispanic white", 
                                                ifelse(DEM_RACE == 2, "Non-Hispanic black", 
                                                       ifelse(DEM_RACE == 3, "Hispanic",
                                                       "Other")))),
                      levels = c("Non-Hispanic white", "Non-Hispanic black", "Hispanic", "Other")
                    )) %>%
  
  # Drop old variables
  select(-DEM_INCOME, -DEM_RACE, ) %>%
  # Melt data to long format
  melt(data = .,
       id.vars = c("PUF_ID", "DEM_SEX", "income", "race"),
       variable.name = "question",
       value.name = "response") %>%
  mutate(
    # Recode numerical responses to character strings
    response2 = (ifelse(is.na(response), "Missing",
                        ifelse(response == 1, "Very Satisfied",
                               ifelse(response == 2, "Satisfied",
                                      ifelse(response == 3, "Dissatisfied", "Very Dissatisfied"))))),
    # Reorder factors
    response3 = factor(response2, levels = c("Missing", "Very Satisfied", "Satisfied", 
                                             "Dissatisfied", "Very Dissatisfied"))
    
  ) 


# Create a frequency table for first items
medicare_night <- data_long %>%
  filter(question == "ACC_MCAVAIL") %>%
  group_by(income, race, response3) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(Freq = n())
  
# Create an alluvial plot
p9 <- ggplot(medicare_night,
       aes(y = Freq, axis1 = income, axis2 = race, axis3 = response3)) +
  geom_alluvium(aes(fill = income), width = 1/12) +
  geom_stratum(width = 1/12, fill = "black", color = "grey") +
  geom_label(stat = "stratum", aes(label = after_stat(stratum))) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = c("Income", "Race", "Satisfaction"), expand = c(.1, .1)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(type = "qual", palette = "Set2") +
  ggtitle("Medicare at night and weekends") +
  theme(legend.position="none")


# Create a frequency table for second items
easy_doctor_home <- data_long %>%
  filter(question == "ACC_MCEASE") %>%
  group_by(income, race, response3) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(Freq = n())
  
# Create an alluvial plot
p10 <- ggplot(easy_doctor_home,
       aes(y = Freq, axis1 = income, axis2 = race, axis3 = response3)) +
  geom_alluvium(aes(fill = income), width = 1/12) +

As shown in the table above, it could be deduced that the probability that one out three of patients with income level less than 25,000 who have access to the different insurance coverage plans are less than 0.50 compared with patients with income level of 25,000 and above. This implies that it is not certain than one out of three patients with less than 25,000 income level benefit from any of the insurance coverage plan. This also applies to the patients with higher income level, the probability that one out of the patients enrolled for any of the insurance coverage is low except for the ‘Insurance Coverage with Medicare Advantage enrollment’ and ‘Insurance Coverage with one or more plans’.

Looking at the insurance coverage with vision, it could be deduced that the probability that one out of three patients of less than 25,000 income level is zero. This implies that it’s possible that none of the three patients picked at random have access to the insurance coverage plans. Also, the probability of the patients of higher income level is really low. This also implies that insurance coverage with vision is generally not accessible to the patients irrespective of their income level.

It is of interest to explore the accessibility of theses insurance coverage plans for each income group putting some demographic characteristics into consideration.

Including the demographic characteristics, gender gave a useful insight as shown in the result above.

For both gender, the probability that one out of three patients with income level less than 25,000 who have access to insurance coverage with private plan that covers Rx Drugs, Nursing Home, Vision, and Dental are all below 0.50 which means that none of three of these patients in these categories have access to the 4 private coverage plans. However, both gender patients with income value of 25,000 and above who have access to the insurance coverage with Rx Drugs seems to have high probability if 1 out 3 is picked at random.

Across the 4 categories above, the probability that 1 out of 3 of the patients irrespective of their income level and gender with insurance coverage plan that covers nursing home and vision are low; this can lead to a conclusion that these 2 coverage plans are most likely not accessible to the patients irrespective of their gender and income level.

It could be noted that the probability that 1 out of 3 of both gender at both income level who have access to the insurance coverage plan enrolled in Medicare Advantage only are high. Hence, it could be deduced that there’s high chances that 1 out of 3 of the patients in these category have access to the insurance coverage plan of enrolled in Medicare Advantage irrespective of their income level and gender.

Looking at patients that enrolled in one or more private plans, it could be deduced that the probability that 1 out of 3 male with less than 25,000 income level have access to the insurance coverage is low unlike other categories of patients.

As deduced from the result above, it is not obvious that there are differences in the insurance coverage plan based on income level and gender.

The result above shows the analysis in the insurance coverage plan based on both income level and three race group, Non-Hispanic White(W), Non-Hispanic Black(B) and Hispanic(H).

For Insurance coverage plan with Rx Drugs and dental, it could be deduced that the probability that 1 out of 3 patients with less than 25,000 income level irrespective of their race is low which implies that the likelihood of such patients having access to the insurance coverage plan with Rx Drugs and dental is not certain unlike the patients with 25,000 or more income level across all three races. The probability of 1 out 3 patients with high income level despite race group difference is high, hence there’s likelihood that 1 out of 3 patients would have access to the insurance coverage with Rx Drugs and dental.

In the case of the insurance coverage with nursing home and vision, the probability that 1 out of 3 from patients with both income group irrespective of their race (W,B or H) are all low which implies that there is no likelihood that 1 out of 3 of these patients had access to any of these insurance coverage plan (nursing home and vision) irrespective of their income group and race.

For Insurance coverage with Medicare Advantage, the probability that 1 out of 3 from patients with both income level and all race group (W,B or H) are all high which implies that there is high likelihood that 1 out of 3 of the patients had access to the insurance coverage plan with Medicare Advantage irrespective of their race and income level.

For Insurance coverage with one or more private plan, the probability that 1 out of 3 from patients with 25,000 and more income level and the three race group (W,B or H) are all high which implies that there is high likelihood that 1 out of 3 of the patients had access to the insurance coverage plan with one or more private plan. This is also applicable to only Non-Hispanic White (W) with less than 25,000 income level while other race (B and H) with less than 25,000 income level are not likely to have access to insurance coverage with one or more private plan.

Largely speaking, the income level and demographic characteristics do not have any significant effect on the insurance coverage types.


Inference statistic


For a more accurate answer to our question, hypothesis test will be carried out as follows using two proportion z-test.

Hnull: There is no difference in the insurance coverage types between the two income groups Halternative: There is difference in the insurance coverage types between the two income groups

Click here to see the code 


#HYPOTHESIS TESTING FOR INCOME GROUP

#Insurance Coverage Plan with Private Plan that covers Rx drugs
INS_PRIVRX_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(INS_PRIVRX == 1)
INS_PRIVRX_MORE25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 2) %>%
  tally(INS_PRIVRX == 1)

n_trials <- nrow(df)

INS_PRIVRX_TEST <- prop.test(x = c(INS_PRIVRX_LESS25$n, INS_PRIVRX_MORE25$n), n = c(n_trials, n_trials), alternative = 'two.sided', correct = TRUE)

#Insurance Coverage Plan with Private Plan that covers Nursing Home
INS_PRIVLTC_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(INS_PRIVLTC == 1)

  tally(INS_PRIVLTC == 1)

n_trials <- nrow(df)

#Insurance Coverage Plan with Private Plan that covers Vision

  tally(INS_PRIVVIS == 1)

n_trials <- nrow(df)

#Insurance Coverage Plan with Private Plan that covers Dental

  tally(INS_D_PRIVNUM == 1)

INS_D_PRIVNUM_TEST <- prop.test(x = c(INS_D_PRIVNUM_LESS25$n, INS_D_PRIVNUM_MORE25$n), n = c(n_trials, n_trials), alternative = 'two.sided', correct = TRUE)

Following the hypothesis testing result above, it could be inferred that with significance level of 0.05, we will accept the null hypothesis that there is no difference in the insurance coverage types between the two income groups for the Insurance coverage with Rx Drugs, Nursing Home, Vision and Medicare Advantage. #PROBABILITIES FOR INCOME GROUP LESS THAN 25.000

##Satisfaction with medical care night/weekend
ACC_MCAVAIL_PROB1_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(ACC_MCAVAIL == 1 | ACC_MCAVAIL == 2) 
ACC_MCAVAIL_PROB1_LESS25 <- round(ACC_MCAVAIL_PROB1_LESS25 / tally(df),2)
ACC_MCAVAIL_PROB1_LESS25 <- round((1-(1-ACC_MCAVAIL_PROB1_LESS25)^3),2)

##Satisfaction with easy to get a doctor from home

According to the previous table, it is observed that when selecting three patients at random, the probability that one of them is satisfied or very satisfied with the variables analyzed for each income group and comparing race is very high and very similar between them. Therefore, we can preliminary conclude that there is no difference in the level of satisfaction when comparing by income group and race. However, this theory will be tested by applying statistical inference.


Inference statistic


We are going to answer the question by applying hypothesis testing. Our null hypothesis is that there is not differences between the two income groups about the satisfaction of the medicare services. We will apply the two proportion z-test for each of the variables of our interest.

Click here to see the code 


#Medicare at night/weekend
ACC_MCAVAIL_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(ACC_MCAVAIL == 1 | ACC_MCAVAIL == 2) 
ACC_MCAVAIL_MORE25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 2) %>%
  tally(ACC_MCAVAIL == 1 | ACC_MCAVAIL == 2) 

n_trials <- nrow(df)

ACC_MCAVAIL_TEST <- prop.test(x = c(ACC_MCAVAIL_LESS25$n, ACC_MCAVAIL_MORE25$n), n = c(n_trials, n_trials), alternative = 'two.sided', correct = TRUE)


#easy to get a doctor from home
ACC_MCEASE_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(ACC_MCEASE == 1 | ACC_MCEASE == 2) 
ACC_MCEASE_MORE25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 2) %>%
  tally(ACC_MCEASE == 1 | ACC_MCEASE == 2) 


ACC_MCEASE_TEST <- prop.test(x = c(ACC_MCEASE_LESS25$n, ACC_MCEASE_MORE25$n), n = c(n_trials, n_trials), alternative = 'two.sided', correct = TRUE)

#OOP costs
ACC_MCCOSTS_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(ACC_MCCOSTS == 1 | ACC_MCCOSTS == 2) 
ACC_MCCOSTS_MORE25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 2) %>%
  tally(ACC_MCCOSTS == 1 | ACC_MCCOSTS == 2) 


ACC_MCCOSTS_TEST <- prop.test(x = c(ACC_MCCOSTS_LESS25$n, ACC_MCCOSTS_MORE25$n), n = c(n_trials, n_trials), alternative = 'two.sided', correct = TRUE)


#Medicare at same location 
ACC_MCSAMLOC_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(ACC_MCCOSTS == 1 | ACC_MCSAMLOC == 2) 
ACC_MCSAMLOC_MORE25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 2) %>%
  tally(ACC_MCCOSTS == 1 | ACC_MCSAMLOC == 2) 


ACC_MCSAMLOC_TEST <- prop.test(x = c(ACC_MCSAMLOC_LESS25$n, ACC_MCSAMLOC_MORE25$n), n = c(n_trials, n_trials), alternative = 'two.sided', correct = TRUE)

##Join the outputs in one column
ACC_TEST1 <- data.frame(rbind(ACC_MCAVAIL_TEST$p.value, ACC_MCEASE_TEST$p.value,ACC_MCCOSTS_TEST$p.value, ACC_MCSAMLOC_TEST$p.value))

##formating and join the two outputs in a data frame
ACC_TEST1 <- data.frame(cbind(criterias, ACC_TEST1))
names(ACC_TEST1)[1]<-paste("Evaluated criterion")
names(ACC_TEST1)[2]<-paste("P Value")



Considering the above table, we can conclude that at the 5% of significance, from the sample data, there is sufficient evidence to conclude that there is a difference between proportion of satisfaction for both income groups.

For all races the P value is less than our confidence level of 5%. That means the hypothesis has to be reject, in other words, there is sufficient evidence to conclude that there is a difference between proportion of satisfaction for both income groups in all races.

According to the previous table, it is observed that when selecting three patients at random, the probability that one of them has a insurance that covers dental and eye exam for each income group and comparing race is very high and very similar between them. Therefore, we can preliminary conclude that there is no difference in the level of coverage when comparing by income group and race. However, this theory will be tested by applying statistical inference.


Inference statistic


We are going to answer the question by applying hypothesis testing. Our null hypothesis is that there is not differences between the two income groups about the coverage of the of the medicare advantage plan. We will apply the two proportion z-test for each of the variables of our interest.

Click here to see the code 


#Medicare Adv plan covers dental
MA_MADVDENT_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(MA_MADVDENT == 1) 
MA_MADVDENT_MORE25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 2) %>%
  tally(MA_MADVDENT == 1) 

n_trials <- df %>% tally(INS_D_MADV == 1)


MA_MADVDENT_TEST <- prop.test(x = c(MA_MADVDENT_LESS25$n, MA_MADVDENT_MORE25$n), n = c(n_trials$n, n_trials$n), alternative = 'two.sided', correct = TRUE)


#Medicare Adv plan covers eye exam
MA_MADVEYE_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(MA_MADVEYE == 1) 
MA_MADVEYE_MORE25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 2) %>%
  tally(MA_MADVEYE == 1) 


MA_MADVEYE_TEST <- prop.test(x = c(MA_MADVEYE_LESS25$n, MA_MADVEYE_MORE25$n), n = c(n_trials$n, n_trials$n), alternative = 'two.sided', correct = TRUE)

#Medicare Adv plan covers nursing at home
MA_MADVNH_LESS25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 1) %>%
  tally(MA_MADVNH == 1) 
MA_MADVNH_MORE25 <- df %>% filter(DEM_INCOME == 2) %>%
  tally(MA_MADVNH == 1) 


MA_MADVNH_TEST <- prop.test(x = c(MA_MADVNH_LESS25$n, MA_MADVNH_MORE25$n), n = c(n_trials$n, n_trials$n), alternative = 'two.sided', correct = TRUE)


##Join the outputs in one column
AM_TEST1 <- data.frame(rbind(MA_MADVDENT_TEST$p.value, MA_MADVEYE_TEST$p.value,MA_MADVNH_TEST$p.value))

##formating and join the two outputs in a data frame
AM_TEST1 <- data.frame(cbind(criterias, AM_TEST1))
names(AM_TEST1)[1]<-paste("Evaluated criterion")
names(AM_TEST1)[2]<-paste("P Value")



Considering the above table, we can conclude that at the 5% of significance, from the sample data, there is sufficient evidence to conclude that there is a difference between proportion of satisfaction for both income groups.

names(MA_TEST2)[2]<-paste("P Value | MALE")
names(MA_TEST2)[3]<-paste("P Value | FEMALE")



Considering the above table, we can conclude that at the 5% of significance, from the sample data, there is sufficient evidence to conclude that there is a difference between proportion of coverage in the medicare advantage plan for both income groups when referring to males and females.
